## Summary of Tuicraft Codebase Patterns for Guild Roster Support

Based on my thorough exploration of the tuicraft codebase, here are the key patterns relevant to implementing guild roster support:

---

## 1. Opcode Definition and Registration Pattern

**File**: `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/protocol/opcodes.ts`

Opcodes are defined as constants in a single file organized by system:

```typescript
export const GameOpcode = {
  // Guild-related opcodes are already defined:
  CMSG_GUILD_ROSTER: 0x089,
  SMSG_GUILD_ROSTER: 0x08a,
  CMSG_GUILD_CREATE: 0x081,
  CMSG_GUILD_INVITE: 0x082,
  SMSG_GUILD_INVITE: 0x083,
  // ... more guild opcodes

  // Similar pattern for groups:
  CMSG_GROUP_INVITE: 0x06e,
  SMSG_GROUP_LIST: 0x07d,
  // ... etc
};
```

The opcodes are registered in `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/client.ts` using the `dispatch.on()` method (lines 357-439):

```typescript
conn.dispatch.on(GameOpcode.SMSG_GROUP_LIST, (r) =>
  handleGroupListMsg(conn, r),
);
```

---

## 2. Roster-Like Feature Pattern: Group/Party Members

**Files**: 
- `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/protocol/group.ts` - Protocol parsing
- `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts` - Event handling
- `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/client.ts` - Storage and dispatch

The group roster pattern shows the exact structure for guild rosters:

```typescript
// Protocol definition (group.ts)
export type GroupMember = {
  name: string;
  guidLow: number;
  guidHigh: number;
  online: boolean;
};

export type GroupList = {
  members: GroupMember[];
  leaderGuidLow: number;
  leaderGuidHigh: number;
};

export function parseGroupList(r: PacketReader): GroupList {
  // ... parse member count
  const members: GroupMember[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < memberCount; i++) {
    const name = r.cString();
    const guidLow = r.uint32LE();
    const guidHigh = r.uint32LE();
    const online = r.uint8() !== 0;
    // ... skip metadata
    members.push({ name, guidLow, guidHigh, online });
  }
  // ... parse leader
  return { members, leaderGuidLow, leaderGuidHigh };
}
```

The roster is stored in `WorldConn` directly:

```typescript
// client.ts lines 196-223
export type WorldConn = {
  partyMembers: Map<string, { guidLow: number; guidHigh: number }>;
  // ... other fields
};
```

---

## 3. Data Store Pattern: FriendStore as Template

**File**: `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/friend-store.ts`

This is the best template for guild roster storage. It provides:

```typescript
export type FriendEntry = {
  guid: bigint;
  name: string;
  note: string;
  status: number;
  area: number;
  level: number;
  playerClass: number;
};

export type FriendEvent =
  | { type: "friend-list"; friends: FriendEntry[] }
  | { type: "friend-online"; friend: FriendEntry }
  | { type: "friend-offline"; guid: bigint; name: string }
  | { type: "friend-added"; friend: FriendEntry }
  | { type: "friend-removed"; guid: bigint; name: string }
  | { type: "friend-error"; result: number; name: string };

export class FriendStore {
  private friends: Map<bigint, FriendEntry>;
  private listener?: (event: FriendEvent) => void;

  set(entries: FriendEntry[]): void { /* bulk load */ }
  add(entry: FriendEntry): void { /* single add */ }
  update(guid: bigint, fields: FriendUpdateFields): void { /* update */ }
  remove(guid: bigint): void { /* remove */ }
  findByName(name: string): FriendEntry | undefined { }
  all(): FriendEntry[] { /* sorted */ }
}
```

This pattern should be replicated for `GuildRosterStore`.

